i## title: CHIP-8 emulator	/	tilde.team	70
i## date: "2023-03-08"	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI wanted to learn the basics of emulator development and	/	tilde.team	70
iemulation in general. So I decided to make a CHIP-8 emulator.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iIn fact it's a misuse of language to say that it's an	/	tilde.team	70
iemulator because CHIP-8 is a language, so we should rather	/	tilde.team	70
isay interpreter.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## How does it work ?	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iSo, basically there are three main components that make it	/	tilde.team	70
iworks. The CPU, the API and the Core (kernel).	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThe API polls the keyboard inputs and send them to the CPU	/	tilde.team	70
ithat put them in the right memory location.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThe CPU fetch, decode and execute an instruction from a ROM	/	tilde.team	70
i(program or game), it can change the VRAM and the CPU	/	tilde.team	70
iregisters, etc ..	/	tilde.team	70
iDepending of the CPU state, the window draw the VRAM	/	tilde.team	70
ithrought the API.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThere are approximately n instructions executed per second	/	tilde.team	70
ifor a frequency of n hz (n is 500 by default). The sound and	/	tilde.team	70
idelay timers are managed with 60hz.	/	tilde.team	70
